</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32B657DFFB7FF83099EF92DFE75FBC5" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8E36F6FFB7FF83099EF92DFE75FBC5" blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis id="B945EAE4FFB7FF83099EF92DFE89FBE1" bold="true" box="[199,334,1087,1113]" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="B945EAE4FFB7FF830A14F92DFC4AFBE1" box="[845,909,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">ferro-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B945EAE4FFB7FF830A9BF92DFC3BFBE1" box="[962,1020,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">rufus</emphasis>
, referring to the forewing having two ferrugineous red patches.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
